<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-228-153 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 825 547</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Feb 1 1991 v140 pC3(N) pD3(L) 14 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus posts its first loss for a quarter; deficit is attributed to$53 million write-off on Samna acquisition. (Lotus DevelopmentCorp.)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Lotus Development Corp reports the first quarterly loss in thesoftware publisher's history.andP;  Lotus loses $31.6 million, comparedto a profit of $29.4 million in the same quarter a year earlier.andO;For 1990, Lotus reports earnings of $23.3 million or 54 cents ashare, compared to $68 million and $1.61 a share in 1989.andO;According to Chmn Jim P. Manzi, the loss is not significant.andO;Manzi says the quarterly loss is a result of a $53 millionwrite-off charged to the cost of last year's acquisition of SamnaCorp, an Atlanta-based company that makes Ami Pro, the wordprocessor.andP;  Otherwise, sales are up.andP;  Nevertheless, industryanalysts express doubts about the long-term status of Lotus andbelieve a Lotus spreadsheet product that supports the MicrosoftWindows graphical user interface is necessary to the company'sfinancial well-being.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (Finance).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Topic:     ProfitLossesSoftware PublishersFinancial Report.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>